{{about|the metalworking tool}} [[File:Francisco de Goya y Lucientes - Knife Grinder - WGA10060.jpg|upright|thumb|Man using a portable grindstone; painting by [[Goya]]]] [[File:Finch Foundry, grindstone.jpg|upright|thumb|Large waterwheel powered grindstone. The user would lie on the plank above the grindstone while grinding metal items, giving rise to the phrase [[wiktionary:nose to the grindstone|nose to the grindstone]].<ref>[http://www.phrases.org.uk/meanings/217200.html]</ref>]]
A '''grindstone''' is a round [[sharpening stone]] used for [[Grinding (abrasive cutting)|grinding]] or sharpening [[ferrous]] [[tool]]s. Grindstones are usually made from [[sandstone]].<ref>{{Citation|title=Grindstones |url=http://scholar.chem.nyu.edu/tekpages/grindstone.html |accessdate=2010-02-10 |archiveurl=https://www.webcitation.org/5nRSwhf4Y?url=http://scholar.chem.nyu.edu/tekpages/grindstone.html |archivedate=2010-02-10 |postscript=. |deadurl=yes |df= }}</ref><ref>{{Citation | last = Knight | first = Edward Henry | title = Knight's American mechanical dictionary | pages = 1022–1023 | publisher = Houghton, Mifflin | year = 1876 | url = https://books.google.com/books?id=7jZVAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA1022 | postscript =.}}</ref> Grindstone machines usually have [[pedal]]s for speeding up and slowing down the stone to control the sharpening process. The earliest known representation of a rotary grindstone,<ref name="White, Jr. 1962, 110">{{harvnb|White, Jr.|1962|p=110}}</ref> operated by a crank handle, is found in the [[Carolingian dynasty|Carolingian]] manuscript ''[[Utrecht Psalter]]''. This pen drawing from about 830 goes back to a late antique original.<ref>{{harvnb|Hägermann|Schneider|1997|pp=425f.}}</ref> The ''[[Luttrell Psalter]]'', dating to around 1340, describes a grindstone rotated by two cranks, one at each end of its axle.<ref name="White, Jr. 1962, 111">{{harvnb|White, Jr.|1962|p=111}}</ref> Around 1480, the early medieval rotary grindstone was improved with a [[treadle]] and [[crank mechanism]].<ref>{{harvnb|White, Jr.|1962|p=167}}</ref>
