{{Orphan|date=September 2016}}
{{Infobox person |name = Richard Handl |image = |image_size = |caption = |birth_date = |birth_place = |residence = |nationality = |other_names = |known_for = Nuclear experimentation at home |education = }}
'''Richard Handl''' (born 23 May 1980) is a [[Swedes|Swedish]] man who experimented with building a [[breeder reactor]] in his apartment in [[Ängelholm]], [[Sweden]] for six months in 2011 with the intention to create a nuclear reaction.<ref name=abcau>[http://www.abc.net.au/news/2011-08-05/swedish-kitchen-nuke-reactor/2825356 "Man tries to build nuke reactor in kitchen"]. ''ABC News''.</ref><ref name=swedishwire>Johan Nylander. [http://www.swedishwire.com/science/10855-swede-tried-to-build-nuke-reactor-in-kitchen "Swede tried to build nuke reactor in kitchen"].</ref>
After working in a factory for four years,<ref name="Ronson2012">{{cite book|author=Jon Ronson|title=Lost at Sea: The Jon Ronson Mysteries|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ILTEbokLCBsC&pg=PT205|date=30 October 2012|publisher=Penguin Group US|isbn=978-1-101-61242-2|pages=205–}}</ref><ref name=telegraphuk>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/newstopics/howaboutthat/8679630/Swedish-man-arrested-after-trying-to-split-atoms-in-his-kitchen.html "Swedish man arrested after trying to split atoms in his kitchen"]. ''Telegraph.co.uk''. 3 August 2011.</ref> Handl became unemployed and decided to start a collection of the elements on the periodic table.<ref>Jon Ronson. [https://www.theguardian.com/science/2012/feb/03/jon-ronson-diy-science-experiments "DIY science: should you try this at home?"]. ''the Guardian''.</ref> Out of curiosity he began experimenting with his collected elements to see if he could create a nuclear reaction.<ref name=bbc>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-14406766 "BBC News - Swede admits home-made atom experiment was 'crazy'"]. ''BBC News''.</ref>
Handl's experiment included the acquisition of fissile material from outside the country,<ref name=scidaily>[http://www.sciencenewsdaily.org/internet-news/cluster108635190/ "Science News Daily"].</ref> a radiator suitable for [[Nuclear transmutation|transmutation]], and instruments to measure the reaction, including a [[Geiger counter]].<ref name=theaustralian>[http://www.theaustralian.com.au/news/breaking-news/swedish-man-detained-for-building-nuclear-reactor-in-kitchen/story-fn3dxity-1226107009015 "Swedish man detained for building nuclear reactor in kitchen,"]. ''The Australian News''.</ref> He spent about 5000 to 6,000 Swedish kronor in materials and equipment.<ref name=businessinsider>[http://www.businessinsider.com/sweden-nuclear-reactor-angelholm-2011-8 "The Weird Story Of The Swedish Man Who Tried To Build A Nuclear Reactor In His Kitchen"]. ''Business Insider''. 2 August 2011.</ref> Experiments were done with [[tritium]], [[americium]], [[aluminium]], [[beryllium]], [[thorium]], [[radium]], and [[uranium]], most of which he acquired from foreign companies.<ref name=dn>[http://www.dn.se/nyheter/sverige/tankte-bygga-karnreaktor-i-koket "Tänkte bygga kärnreaktor i köket"]. ''DN.SE''.</ref> One step involved cooking americium, radium and beryllium in {{nowrap|96% [[sulfuric acid]]}} on a [[Electric stove|stove]] in order to more easily mix the ingredients; this resulted in an explosion.<ref name=usatoday>[http://content.usatoday.com/communities/ondeadline/post/2011/08/swedish-man-arrested-for-kitchen-nuclear-reactor/1 "Swedish man arrested over kitchen nuclear 'reactor'"]. ''USATODAY.COM''.</ref> He kept a blog called "Richard's Reactor" in which he documented the progress of the reactor.<ref name=businessinsider /><ref name=wired>[https://www.wired.co.uk/news/archive/2011-08/03/sweden-nuclear-reactor "Swede detained for building nuclear reactor in kitchen"]. ''Wired UK''.</ref>
On 22 July 2011 he was detained by the police<ref>[http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2022333/Richard-Handl-arrested-home-nuclear-reactor.html "Richard Handl arrested for home-made nuclear reactor | Daily Mail Online"]. ''Mail Online''.</ref> after having contacted the [[Swedish Radiation Safety Authority]] (SSM) to inquire as to whether his project was legal or not.<ref name="Shepherd2012">{{cite book|author=Chuck Shepherd|title=News of the Weird: Ironies|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=-nB2QAYXEvgC&pg=PT16|date=18 December 2012|publisher=Andrews McMeel Publishing|isbn=978-1-4494-3779-4|pages=16–}}</ref><ref name=guardian>[https://www.theguardian.com/world/2011/aug/03/atom-splitting-attempt-swedish-kitchen "Atom splitting in my kitchen was a hobby, man tells Swedish police"]. ''the Guardian''.</ref> His apartment was searched, and the radioactive materials as well as his computer were taken by the police.<ref name=bbc/> He was released,<ref>[http://rt.com/news/kitchen-nuclear-reactor-handl/ "Kitchen nuclear reactor leaves Swede handcuffed"]. ''RT News''.</ref><ref>Charles Wilson. [http://www.abacusnews.com/news/11/016-hobby-from-hell.php "Hobbies from Hell | Nuclear Reactor in Kitchen"].</ref><ref name=thelocal[>[http://www.thelocal.se/20110805/35368 "Swede speaks out about kitchen nuclear reactor "]. ''The Local''.</ref> then convicted in July 2014 on the violation of the radiation safety act and the violation of [[:sv:Miljöbalken|Swedish Environmental Code]]. A fine of 13,600 [[Swedish krona|kronor]] was imposed.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/file/d/0B3-9YUgtqBa0RVJWWWpQRmIyczg/edit?pli=1|title=Court decision|accessdate=May 23, 2015}}</ref> ==See also== *[[David Hahn]] == References ==
